# adjust the data types

## change the string of start time & end time to datetimes 

df['start_time'] = df.start_time.astype('datetime64[ns]')

df['end_time'] = df.end_time.astype('datetime64[ns]')

## change the floating member_birth_year and stations IDs to int
df['member_birth_year'] = df.member_birth_year.astype('int32')

df['start_station_id'] = df.start_station_id.astype('int32')

df['end_station_id'] = df.end_station_id.astype('int32')

Adding derived columns¶

In [16]:
# Roll up the duration dimension to the level of the minutes
df['duration_in_mins'] = round(df['duration_sec']/60,2)

# Add new dimension, the member age

from datetime import date

df['member_age'] = int(str(date.today())[:4]) - df['member_birth_year']

# Distribute the age in buckets ranging from younger than 30 years old to older than 70 yeras old.
age_bins= [20,30,40,50,60,70,999]
age_buckets_labels = ['<30','<40','<50','<60', '<70', '>70']
df ['member_age_bucket' ] = pd.cut(df['member_age'], bins = age_bins, labels=age_buckets_labels, right=False)


# The distance can be calculated based on the latitude and longitude of the start and end stations 

df['trip_distance'] = np.sqrt((df.start_station_latitude - df.end_station_latitude)**2 + (df.start_station_longitude - df.end_station_longitude)**2 )*100

# Adding the proper order of the weekdays
weekdays_order = ['Monday', 'Tuesday', 'Wednesday', 'Thursday', 'Friday', 'Saturday', 'Sunday']


# Adding some new dimension rolled up from the start time data.
df['trip_start_day']  = df.start_time.dt.day_name()

df['trip_start_hour'] = df.start_time.dt.hour

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 trips in the dataset (after cleaning) with many features to analyze. We can categorize the data as below:

  • Time information
    • start_time the time of starting the trip.
    • end_time the time of ending the trip.
    • trip_start_day the weekday of the trip.
    • trip_start_hour the hour of day of the trip.
  • Trip Information
    • start_station_id the ID of the starting station.
    • start_station_name the name of starting station.
    • start_station_latitude the latitude of the starting station location.
    • start_station_longitdue the longitude of the starting station location.
    • end_station_id the ID of the end station.
    • end_station_name the name of end station.
    • end_station_latitude the latitude of the end station location.
    • end_station_longitdue the longitude of the end station location.
    • duration_sec the trip duration in seconds.
    • duration_in_mins the trip duration in minutes.
    • trip_distance the trip distance based on "Distance Formula": $\sqrt{(lat_{end} - lat_{start})^2 + (long_{end} - long_{start})^2}$.
  • Member Information
    • member_gender the gender of the member, it is male, female or other.
    • member_birth_year the member's birth year.
    • user_type the member's type, customer or subscriber.
    • member_age a new derived field to hold the member age, year(today) - member birth year.
    • member_age_bucket a new derived field, a category of the member ages to make the analysis easier.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I beleive analyzing the dataset against the member information (age, gender and type) and trip information (distance, duration and count) will end with rich insights.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

I believe analyzing the trip duration will support the investigation, I epxect to find a pattern in users behavior affects the trip duration.

Univariate Exploration¶

In [17]:
## show countplot of a dimension
main_color = '#33A8FF'

def show_countplot (x,figsize=[15,15], title="Put Title", xtitle="", ytitle="", order =[]):
  plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
  sb.countplot(data=df, x=x, color= main_color , order=(df[x].value_counts().index if len(order) == 0 else order))
  plt.title(title)
  plt.xlabel( xtitle)
  plt.ylabel(ytitle)
  plt.show()

def show_pieplot(data_frame,column_name, figsize=[10,10], title=''):
  plt.figure(figsize=figsize)
  labels = data_frame[column_name].value_counts().index
  values = data_frame[column_name].value_counts().values

  plt.title(title)
  plt.pie(values, labels=labels, autopct='%1.2f%%',shadow=True, startangle=0, colors = [main_color, '#9e7a36'])
  plt.show()

Self-Station Trips¶

The self-station trips are the trips when the user rent a bike from a station and then returning it back to the same station.

In [19]:

Most of the users who start and end their trips at the same station are subscribers not ad-hoc customers

from matplotlib import colors

def hist2dgrid(x, y, **kwargs):
    """ Quick hack for creating heat maps with seaborn's PairGrid. """
    palette = kwargs.pop('color')
    
    bins_x = 10
    bins_y = 10 
    plt.hist2d(x, y, bins = [bins_x, bins_y], cmap = palette, cmin = 0.1,  norm = colors.LogNorm())

# show the relationship between the weekday, hour and a trip measure.
import math   

def show_hourly_heatmap (df, dimension_name):
  i = 0
  plt.suptitle('Number of Rides Per Weekday and Hour')

  rows = 1 if math.ceil(len(df[dimension_name].unique())/4)  == 0 else math.ceil(len(df[dimension_name].unique())/4)
  fig,axs = plt.subplots(rows,4, figsize=( 25,5) )
  xvalue = 0
  for val in df[dimension_name].unique():
    if rows ==1 :
      xvalue=axs[i]
    else:
      xvalue = axs[i//4][i%4]
    sb.heatmap(df[df[dimension_name]==val].groupby(['trip_start_day', 'trip_start_hour']).size().reset_index(name='trips_count').pivot(index='trip_start_day', columns='trip_start_hour', values='trips_count'), cmap='Blues', ax=xvalue)
    xvalue.title.set_text(dimension_name +': '+val)
    i+=1

  

  fig.tight_layout(pad=3.0)
  
  fig.show()
